---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { site } from '@/lib/site';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Mining cargo to the DRC — 3 things SA exporters should plan before tendering | Mekluc Insights"
  description="Mining equipment, reagents and consumables flowing into the DRC's copper belt face customs, route and security complexity. We unpack the three planning decisions SA exporters get wrong most often."
>
  <!-- Article hero -->
  <section style="padding-top: clamp(4rem, 9vw, 7rem); padding-bottom: clamp(2.5rem, 5vw, 4rem); background: var(--c-paper);">
    <div class="section">
      <div class="max-w-3xl reveal">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 16px; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          <a href="/insights" style="font-family: var(--f-mono); font-size: 13px; letter-spacing: 0.18em; color: var(--c-bordeaux); text-decoration: none;">&larr; INSIGHTS</a>
          <span style="font-family: var(--f-mono); font-size: 13px; color: var(--c-mute);">&middot;</span>
          <span style="font-family: var(--f-mono); font-size: 13px; letter-spacing: 0.18em; color: var(--c-copper);">CORRIDORS</span>
        </div>
        <h1 style="font-family: var(--f-display); font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3.5rem); font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.1; color: var(--c-ink); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          Mining cargo to the DRC — <em style="color: var(--c-bordeaux); font-style: italic;">3 things</em> SA exporters should plan before tendering
        </h1>
        <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; align-items: center; gap: 14px; font-family: var(--f-mono); font-size: 13px; color: var(--c-mute);">
          <time>May 2026</time>
          <span>&middot;</span>
          <span>~7 min read</span>
          <span>&middot;</span>
          <span>By Mekluc Freight</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Article body -->
  <article style="padding-bottom: clamp(5rem, 12vw, 8rem);">
    <div class="section">
      <div class="max-w-3xl reveal" style="font-family: var(--f-sans); font-size: 1.1875rem; line-height: 1.75; color: var(--c-ink);">

        <p style="font-size: 1.375rem; line-height: 1.55; color: var(--c-charcoal); margin-bottom: 2rem;">
          The DRC copper-cobalt corridor is the most active mining-cargo corridor in Africa right now. Demand for grinding mills, leach reagents, drill consumables and electrical infrastructure into Lualaba and Haut-Katanga has been steady through 2024-2026, and tenders from major operators keep coming. South African exporters — equipment OEMs, chemical distributors, EPCM contractors — are well placed to win the freight side of those tenders. The ones who lose either underestimate three planning decisions or discover them only after the contract is signed.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: var(--f-display); font-size: 1.875rem; font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.2; color: var(--c-ink); margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem;">1. Customs documentation: lock the HS classification before the quote</h2>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
          The DGDA (Direction Générale des Douanes et Accises) does not forgive vague HS classifications. A drill bit declared as <em>industrial tool</em> instead of <em>diamond-tipped mining drill bit, HS 8207.13</em> can be reclassified at the border, attracting punitive duty plus the inevitable demurrage while the dispute is resolved. The classification needs to be agreed with the importer, ideally cross-checked with the DGDA inspecting officer at the destination border post, <em>before</em> the freight quote is given.
        </p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
          For chemicals — reagents, flotation agents, cyanide compounds, sulphuric acid — add two layers: the dangerous goods classification (UN number + packing group) and the import permit issued by the relevant DRC ministry. Cyanide compounds in particular require both DGDA clearance and an OCC environmental permit. Quoting freight on a chemical shipment without the import permit already in motion is a guaranteed contract delay.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: var(--f-display); font-size: 1.875rem; font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.2; color: var(--c-ink); margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem;">2. Route selection: don't default to Durban-Kasumbalesa</h2>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
          The Durban–Beit Bridge–Kasumbalesa route is the historical default — and the most congested. Truck queues at Kasumbalesa frequently exceed five days during peak season. For time-sensitive cargo, three alternatives are worth pricing on every tender:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; list-style: disc;">
          <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Beira (Mozambique) → Kasumbalesa</strong> — shorter inland leg, lower port congestion, suitable for project cargo above 12 m or over 40 tonnes.</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Walvis Bay (Namibia) → Kasumbalesa via the Trans-Kalahari</strong> — strong choice for cargo originating in Western Cape or Gauteng-bound westward, fewer border bottlenecks.</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Air via OR Tambo → Lubumbashi (FBM)</strong> — only economically viable for high-value low-volume cargo (precision instruments, spares, samples) but cuts transit to 36-48 hours door to door.</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
          The optimal route depends on the cargo profile, the mine's location and the season. A tender that prices only the default Durban-Kasumbalesa option leaves margin on the table on both sides.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: var(--f-display); font-size: 1.875rem; font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.2; color: var(--c-ink); margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem;">3. Insurance and security: ICC(A) is not enough</h2>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
          Standard marine cargo insurance under Institute Cargo Clauses (A) covers most maritime perils but leaves significant gaps on the inland leg through Zambia and the DRC. The two coverages worth explicitly adding to a mining-cargo project shipment:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; list-style: disc;">
          <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Strikes, riots and civil commotion (SRCC)</strong> — the inland corridors are exposed to local disruption, particularly around the Lubumbashi and Likasi mining hubs.</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Theft and pilferage with declared value</strong> — high-value mining consumables (catalysts, precious-metal-bearing components) are targeted on transit. Declare value, increase deductible if needed, do not skip the rider.</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
          On the operational side, escorted convoys are the norm for cargo above a certain value threshold. The convoy cost is non-negotiable but the security operator selected matters — a vetted operator with active radio links to the receiving mine site is worth its premium.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: var(--f-display); font-size: 1.875rem; font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.2; color: var(--c-ink); margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem;">Plan early, win the tender twice</h2>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
          The freight forwarder you choose for a DRC mining tender shapes the bid as much as the cargo cost itself. Tenders are won on certainty: certainty of customs classification, certainty of inland transit time, certainty of insurance coverage. None of that is decided in the freight quote — it is decided four to six weeks before, in the planning conversation with the forwarder.
        </p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
          Mekluc Freight handles project cargo and mining consumables to the DRC, Zambia and Zimbabwe as one of our three priority service lines. See our <a href="/solutions/mining-project-cargo-africa" style="color: var(--c-bordeaux); font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 3px;">Mining &amp; Project Cargo Africa</a> page for the full service scope, or talk to us before your next tender.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- CTA BAND -->
  <section class="cta-band-bordeaux" style="padding: clamp(5rem, 12vw, 8rem) 0;">
    <div class="absolute right-[-60px] bottom-[-60px] select-none pointer-events-none" aria-hidden="true">
      <span style="font-family: var(--f-display); font-size: 400px; line-height: 1; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; color: rgba(247,242,232,0.04);">M</span>
    </div>
    <div class="section relative z-10" style="text-align: center;">
      <h2 style="font-family: var(--f-display); font-weight: 400; font-size: clamp(2rem, 4.5vw, 3.25rem); line-height: 1.05; color: var(--c-cream); margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Tendering on a <em style="color: var(--c-copper); font-style: italic;">DRC mining contract?</em>
      </h2>
      <p style="font-family: var(--f-sans); font-size: clamp(0.9375rem, 1.4vw, 1.0625rem); line-height: 1.65; color: rgba(247,242,232,0.7); max-width: 48ch; margin: 0 auto 2.5rem;">
        Pre-tender freight planning conversation — no commitment. We bring 19 years of African corridor experience to the table.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-4">
        <a href="/contact?quote=1" class="btn-white">Start a conversation <span class="btn-arrow">&rarr;</span></a>
        <a href="/solutions/mining-project-cargo-africa" class="btn-outline-light">Mining solutions</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
